We recommended that Management:
Direct officers and employees with cash advances to immediately submit their liquidation papers or refund the amount, otherwise, require the immediate withholding of salary of those officers and employees who were unable to comply with the requirement;
Require the Municipal Accountant to closely monitor the liquidation of outstanding cash advances and send written demand on the submission of liquidation report within the reglementary period;
Stop the practice of granting additional cash advances to those who have unliquidated cash advances and take legal actions against former employees, who are no longer in the government service, with unliquidated cash advances; and
Fast track the recovery of the documents relevant to the cash advances of the deceased and separated accountable officers and conduct verification, analysis and validation of these cash advances to determine their settlement/collectability and pursue collection, refund or liquidation, if warranted.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Require the LGU officials and employees to submit promptly their claims together with complete relevant supporting documents to the Office of the Municipal Accountant;
Hire additional competent personnel in the Accounting Office to accommodate the voluminous transactions occurring each month in the Municipality, and to hasten the process of submission of the necessary accounts to the Office of the Auditor;
Evaluate the process of preparing the disbursement vouchers, RCIs, RCDs, RAAFs, and relevant documents to prevent further occurrence of this deficiency in the succeeding years and be reminded that processing of vouchers must only be undertaken when they were properly approved and with complete documentation; and
Remind the concerned officials and employees of the administrative or criminal liability, under Section 39 (1) (3) of PD No. 1445 and Article 218 of the Revised Penal Code, as amended by Section 41 of Republic Act (RA) No. 10951, which may be imposed as a consequence of their inability or refusal to render accounts without justifiable cause.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that the disbursements for repairs made by the Municipality are supported with complete and appropriate documentation as prescribed in Section 9.1.3.4 of COA Circular No. 2012-001 and Section 362 Volume I of GAAM;
Direct the Supply Officer/GSO-Designate to submit the Pre-repair Evaluation Reports and the Post-inspection Reports relative to the above-mentioned transactions;
Require that Certificates of Acceptance and RWMs be prepared by the Supply Officer/GSO-Designate and approved by the Local Chief Executive, in case of major repairs and if the repairs need replacement; and
Direct the BAC and other concerned officers to revisit the provisions of 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184, specifically in employing different alternative modes of procurement and their procedures, to ensure its compliance at all times.

We recommended that Management submit to the Office of the Auditor the following documents to support the transactions amounting to ₱5,960,924.04:
For the procurement of food packs:
Program of Work/Detailed Plans/activity design;
Contract/s or purchase orders with specification/details of the articles involved in the procurement, and the date and place of the delivery;
Attendance sheets/Distribution Sheets; and
Fully accomplished Inspection and Acceptance Reports and Delivery Receipts.
For the procurement of medicines and medical supplies;
Properly signed and accomplished Purchase Order, RIS, Inspection and Acceptance Reports, Delivery Receipts; and
The certification from the manufacturer that the supplier is an authorized distributor/dealer of the products/items, for the procurement of medicines.
We also recommended that the ICO-Municipal Accountant ensure that: a) all disbursements made by the Municipality are supported with complete documentation as prescribed in COA Circular No. 2012-001 and COA Circular No. 2009-001; and b) the attached documents are properly signed and accomplished in compliance with the applicable laws and regulations to ascertain the validity, legality and propriety of every transaction made by the Municipality.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the Municipal Accountant to:

Strictly observe the rules and regulation relative to the preparation of the monthly Bank Reconciliation Statements (BRS) and submit the same to COA within the prescribed period;

Regularly obtain copies of Bank Statements from the bank, or make continuous reminder or follow up with the bank if the same are not obtained. If possible, enroll in the online access/services of DBP in order to obtain soft copies of monthly bank statements for all the funds of the LGU; 

Prepare/update the Subsidiary Ledger Cards per bank accounts for all the funds; and


Regular coordination between the Municipal Accountant and Treasurer must be made in order that reconciling cash balances in the respective books and records will be adjusted timely and accordingly.

We recommended that Management:

Strictly comply with the laws, rules and regulation relative to the granting, liquidation and monitoring of cash advances. 

Require the Accountant to devise means or procedure to strengthen the internal control with respect to granting and monitoring of cash advances in order that the data and documents of previous cash advances will not be lost. Ensure that the Cash Advance of retiring, resigning or transferring employee is first settled before approving the clearance from money and property accountability; 

Refrain from granting additional cash advances if the previous cash advance has not been fully settled or liquidated; 

Send demand letters to erring Accountable Officers and Employees requiring them to immediately settle and/or refund the remaining cash advance, otherwise, withhold the salaries of those who neglectfully or intentionally fail to settle their cash advances within the prescribed period after demand;
Evaluate individually the probability of collection of outstanding cash advances especially those Dormant Accounts and send request for write off to COA in accordance with the guidelines and procedures prescribed in COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016; and

Enforce appropriate legal action in order to recover/ settle the unliquidated Cash Advances of liable persons and employees and set as an example to those erring officials and employees that their negligence or failure to liquidate cash advances within the prescribed period has a corresponding adverse consequence.
